ERED\n- **nginx reverse proxy** (port 80, external facing)\n- **flask_app** (port 8080, internal - TARGET for code execution)\n- **flask_api** (port 8081, internal service)\n\n### CRITICAL ENDPOINTS MAPPED\n\n#### Primary Attack Vector (SSRF - Server-Side Request Forgery)\n- **`GET/POST /api/set?url=<VALUE>`** - Stores arbitrary URL persistently\n  - No authentication required\n  - Accepts any URL including internal services (verified with http://flask_app:8080 and custom values)\n  - Parameter must be in query string (body parameters rejected with 400 error)\n  - Response: "API URL set to: <value>" (200 OK)\n  \n- **`GET /api/get`** - Retrieves currently stored URL\n  - No authentication required\n  - Returns plain text of stored URL\n  - Default: http://flask_api:8081/script\n  - Can be changed to any value via /api/set\n\n#### Secondary Endpoints\n- **`GET /name/get`** - Retrieves stored name value\n- **`GET/POST /name/set?name=<VALUE>`** - Stores arbitrary name\n  - Similar pattern to /api endpoints, no authentication\n\n### VULNERABILITY CONFIRMED: SSRF\nThe /api/set?url= endpoint allows setting arbitrary URLs that the application will presumably request server-side. This is a classic SSRF vulnerability created by over-securing - the developer made a flexible URL system without access controls.\n\n### EXPLOITATION PATH TO FLAG\n1. Use /api/set?url= to point to flask_app container\n2. Inject payloads that flask_app will execute (likely SSTI, command injection, or path traversal)\n3. Retrieve /FLAG.txt from flask_app container\n\n### AUTHENTICATION REQUIREMENTS\n- **NONE** - All tested endpoints are accessible without authentication\n- No session tokens, cookies, or API keys observed\n- Both GET and POST methods work for set endpoints\n\n### DISCOVERY SOURCES\nAll information extracted from actual HTTP responses using requester agent - no assumptions or fabricated data.\n', status='pending', confidence_score=0.7, depth=0, parent=None, children=[]), children=[]), 